# Swarm/Drone Orchestration Mission Repository

This repository defines a research-driven, phased architecture for a drone/swarm orchestration stack that unifies three core capability lines:

- Vision-Based Positioning System (VPS) for GPS-denied navigation.
- Direction of Own Artifact (DOOAF) for drone-to-gun directional targeting support.
- Integrated Drone Command and Fleet Management (IIF) for fleet visibility, identification, coordination, and command.

The source DPRs describe VPS as a modular visual-SLAM and sensor-fusion system with MAVLink integration, Jetson-class edge compute, ROS2 middleware, and return-to-home logic in GPS-denied operations; DOOAF as a low-latency targeting and directional vector pipeline built around EO/IR payloads, geolocation, encrypted relay, and ruggedized ground terminals; and IIF as a centralized command layer using MAVLink, ArduPilot, Node.js/Python services, time-series and mission databases, secure telemetry, and C4ISR integration.[file:3][file:2][file:1]

## Repository goals

- Define a mission statement that is technically scoped and deployment-qualified.
- Break the system into layers that can be developed by research and engineering cohorts.
- Provide GitHub-native structure for source control, CI, issues, ADRs, and phased releases.
- Provide Mintlify-compatible documentation scaffolding for architecture, APIs, operations, and deployment.

## Structure

- `MISSION.md` — primary mission/problem statement.
- `design.md` — architecture and design language for docs and system organization.
- `docs/` — Mintlify-ready documentation tree.
- `.github/` — issue templates and docs CI workflow.
- `mint.json` — Mintlify navigation and site config.

## Suggested next implementation tracks

- MCP server layer for mission planning, telemetry normalization, model registry, and policy enforcement.
- Connector layer for MAVLink, ROS2, RF/SATCOM, EO/IR payloads, C4ISR, storage, and observability.
- Simulation and HITL/SITL environments for phased validation before field trials.
